    {
      "title": "Power Absorbed by Battery",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Power Absorbed by Battery&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>When charges are transported across a source of emf, their potential energy changes. If a net charge $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }q$ moves through a potential difference $\\text{E}$ in a time $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ t}$, the change in electric potential energy of the charge is E $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }q$. Thus, the source of emf does work,</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ W}=\\text{E }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ q}$</p><p>Dividing both sides by $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ t}$, then taking the limit as $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ t}\\to 0$, we find,</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{dW}}{\\text{dt}}=\\text{E}\\frac{\\text{dq}}{\\text{dt}}$</p><p>By definition, $\\frac{\\text{dq}}{\\text{dt}}=\\text{i}$, the current through the battery and $\\frac{\\text{dW}}{\\text{dt}}=\\text{P}$, the power output of (or input to) the battery, Hence,</p><p>$\\text{P}=\\text{Ei}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"344\" height=\"151\">&nbsp;</p><p>The quantity $\\text{P}$ represents the rate at which energy is transferred from a discharging battery or to a charging battery.</p><p>Energy is transferred from the source at a rate Ei</p><p>Energy is transferred to the source at a rate Ei.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db38c03b9dcaf1afe0b1"
    },
    {
      "title": "Power Dissipated Across Resistance",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Power Dissipated Across Resistance&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Now let's consider the power dissipated in a conducting element. Suppose it has a resistance $\\text{R}$ and the potential difference between its ends is V. In moving through the element from higher to lower potential, a positive charge $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }q$ loses energy $\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ U}=\\text{V }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ q}$. This electric energy is absorbed by the conductor through collisions between its atomic lattice and the charge carriers, causing its temperature to rise. This effect is commonly called Joule heating. Since power is the rate at which energy is transferred, we have,</p><p>$\\text{P}=\\frac{\\Delta\\text{ U}}{\\Delta\\text{ t}} =\\text{V}\\cdot \\frac{\\Delta\\text{ q}}{\\Delta\\text{ t}}=\\text{Vi}$</p><p>$P=\\text{Vi}$</p><p>which with the help of Ohm's law can also be written in the forms,</p><p>$\\text{P}={{\\text{i}}^{2}}\\text{R }\\text{ or }\\text{ P}=\\frac{{{\\text{V}}^{2}}}{\\text{R}}$</p><p>Power is always dissipated in a resistance. With this rate the heat produced in the resistor in time $t$ is,</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"312\" height=\"96\">&nbsp;</p><p>$\\text{H}=\\text{Pt}$</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} \\text{H}=\\text{Vit}={{\\text{i}}^{2}}\\text{Rt}=\\frac{{{\\text{V}}^{2}}}{\\text{R}}\\text{t} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Joule heating occurs whenever a current passes through an element that has resistance. To prevent the overheating of delicate electronic components, many electric devices like video cassette recorders, televisions and computer monitors have fans in their chassis to allow some of the heat produced to escape.</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db38c03b9dcaf1afe0b2"
    }
  ],
